To get the three python files:
  getSliceData_hdf5.py
  printRegionAndFields.py
  getPointData_hdf5.py
going, following has to be done:

1. Edit ~/.bashrc so python can use vtk. Add the lines:
# Set the paraview directory inside your CFS build directory
export PV_PATH=CFS_BUILD_DIR/paraview
# set the PYTHONPATH
PYTHONPATH=$PYTHONPATH:$PV_PATH/../tmp/build/ParaView3/VTK/Wrapping/Python:$PV_PATH/lib/paraview-3.6/:$PV_PATH/lib/paraview-3.6/paraview
export PYTHONPATH
# set the LD_LIBRARY_PATH
LD_LIBRARY_PATH=$PV_PATH/lib/paraview-3.6/:$PV_PATH/bin/:${HOME}/Pardiso/lib:/opt/pckg/nacsdeps_build/lib64/OPENSUSE_11.0_X86_64
export LD_LIBRARY_PATH

2. Tell CFS NOT to delete the build directory of paraview (CFS_BUILD/tmp/paraview):
comment the line:
    DeleteSubdir("$BUILDDIR/ParaView3");
in the file:
    /opt/CFSDEPS/paraview/build_paraview.pl
This is the standard path of the CFSDEPS directory. Change appropiately to your
system set-up.
If CFS has already been build, remove the paraview directory in the CFS_Build
directory and type:
make
This should generate you CFS_BUILD/tmp/paraview

